In 2020, Democratic presidential nominee Joe Biden was the beneficiary of a massive gender gap that propelled him to the White House. According to exit polls, Donald Trump won men by 8 percentage points (53% to Biden’s 45%) but lost women by 15 points (42% to Biden’s 57%)—a huge 23-point gender gap.&nbsp;



That was before Trump’s largely handpicked Supreme Court overturned Roe v. Wade and ended the constitutional right to abortion, and before the Democratic Party nominated a dynamic woman candidate to face a tired, grumpy Trump in 2024. The result: The latest Quinnipiac University poll has Vice President Kamala Harris winning women by 21 points (58% to Trump’s 37%), and Trump winning men by 18 points (57% to Harris’ 39%)—a yawning 39-point gender gap.&nbsp;



